Antenatal, and Intranatal care Utilization in Turkey using DHS data 2013

Sami Najmaddin Saeed

2026-01-03

1 Introduction:

1.1 Background

An important measure of a countrys overall healthcare progress and social justice is maternal health. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), reducing maternal and neonatal morbidity and mortality requires comprehensive maternal care, including competent attendance at birth and adequate prenatal care (ANC). Data from the 2013 Turkey Demographic and Health Survey (TDHS) show that substantial internal disparities persist within the Turkish population, despite international initiatives that have significantly expanded access to these services.

1.2 General objective:

To describe antenatal and intranatal care utilization among women with a recent live birth in Turkey.

1.3 Specific objectives:

  1. To describe the socio-demographic characteristics of women with a recent live birth.
  2. to describe the prevalance of antenatal care and intranatal care of women with a recent live birth.
  3. To assess antenatal care utilization by maternal age, maternal education, place of residence, and household wealth.
  4. To assess intranatal care utilization by maternal education and place of residence.
  5. To describe the distribution of caesarean section deliveries by maternal education and household wealth.

2 Method:

2.1 Study design and data source:

a cross-sectional descriptive study conducted using secondary data of Turkey Demographic and Health Survey in 2013. The survey collected information on maternal health service utilization, including antenatal and intranatal care

2.2 Study population:

This study include women aged 15-49 years who reported having a recent live birth during the DHS reference period. Women without a recorded live birth were excluded from the analysis.

2.3 Study variables and data analysis:

The outcome variables in this study are antenatal care utilization, intranatal care utilization, and caesarean section delivery. Antenatal care utilization was categorized as fewer than four visits (<4 visits) and four or more visits (4 visits), based on the World Health Organization recommendation at the time of the survey. Intranatal care (INC) was defined as delivery occurring in a health facility and being attended by a skilled health provider (doctor, nurse, or midwife).

The explanatory variables are socio-demographic factors, including maternal age, education level, region, place of residence (urban/rural), household wealth index, marital status, husbands education, and parity.

Descriptive statistics were used to summarize the data. Frequencies and percentages were calculated for categorical variables. Antenatal, intranatal, and caesarean section utilization were presented overall and stratified by selected socio-demographic characteristics using stacked bar charts and donuts chart.

All analyses were conducted using R statistical software.

3 Results:

3.1 Characteristics of the respondents

Table 1 depicts the distribution of ANC and INC utilization and caesarean section delivery among mothers aged 1549 years, along with respondents sociodemographic characteristics. Of the 2,721 mothers included in the study, 89.5% attended four or more ANC visits. Regarding intranatal care, 97.7% of deliveries occurred in a health facility with skilled birth attendance, and nearly 50% of births were by caesarean section. Women aged 2529 years accounted for 30.4% of the sample, while 39.1% and 35.6% had primary and secondary education, respectively. A higher proportion of women lived in urban areas (73.5%) compared with rural areas (26.4%), and 32.9% resided in eastern Turkey. Women in the poorest and poorer wealth categories together accounted for 49% of the sample.

3.2 Plots of maternal care utilization(antenatal and intranatal care and Caesarean Section Delivery) by Selected Variables

3.2.1 Age distribution by ANC utilization

As shown in the box plot distribution (Figure 2), the findings illustrate the relationship between maternal age and the number of antenatal care (ANC) visits. Regardless of whether a woman completed the recommended four ANC visits, the substantial overlap between the two box plots indicates that maternal age does not differ significantly between groups. This suggests that factors other than age influence ANC utilization.

Figure 1: Age distribution by ANC utilization

3.2.2 Antenatal care utilization (4 visits) by maternal education level

The bar graph shows that the proportion of women with higher education level had higher antenatal care utilization 99.1% while lower proportion of women with no education had fewer antenatal care 74.6%.

Figure 2: Antenatal care utilization (4 visits) by maternal education level

3.2.3 Antenatal care by residence

The graph shows antenatal care (ANC) attendance (4 visits) between urban and rural women. Among women living in urban areas, the vast majority (93%) attended at least four antenatal care visits, while only 7% had fewer than four visits. In contrast, antenatal care attendance was lower among rural women, with 79% achieving four or more visits and 21% attending fewer than four visits.

Figure 3: Antenatal care by place of residence

3.2.4 Antenatal Care Utilization by Wealth Index

The distribution of antenatal care adherence (at least four visits) across wealth quintiles in Turkey is illustrated in Figure 4, based on the 2013 Demographic and Health Survey (DHS). The richest quintile achieved the highest rate of coverage at 98.5%, while the poorest quintile had the lowest at 75.4%. This represents a total disparity gap of 23.1 percentage points.

Figure 4: wealth index and antenatal care utiliazation

3.2.5 Intranatal care utilization by maternal education level

Figure 5 illustrates a clear positive association between a womans educational attainment and the likelihood of receiving intranatal care. While utilization rates are high across all groups, significant disparities exist for those with the lowest levels of education. Women in the primary, secondary, and higher education groups have near-total utilization rates of 98.2%, 99.5%, and 99.4%, respectively. In contrast, women in the no education group exhibit the lowest rate of utilization at 89.9%.

Figure 5: Intranatal care utilization and maternal education level

3.2.6 Intranatal care by residence

The graph illustrates the disparity in intranatal care utilization between urban and rural women. Among those living in urban areas, the utilization rate is nearly universal at 99.0%. In contrast, utilization is notably lower among rural women, at 94.2%.

Figure 6: Intranatal care by place of residence

3.2.7 Caesarean Section Delivery by Education Level

There is a notable shift in delivery trends as education levels progress from no formal schooling to higher education. Women in the higher education group have the highest prevalence of Caesarean sections, with 71.6% delivering via this method. In this category, C-sections are more than twice as common as vaginal deliveries (28.4%). Within the secondary education group, C-sections become the majority delivery method, accounting for 51.9% of births. For the primary education group, slightly less than half of the women (45.8%) underwent a C-section. In contrast, women with no formal education have the lowest rate of C-section deliveries at 30.2%, with vaginal delivery remaining the predominant method for this group at 69.8% (Figure 6).

Figure 7: Caesarean section and maternal education

3.2.8 Caesarean Section Delivery by Wealth Index

The graph illustrates a distinct progression in the frequency of C-sections across the five wealth quintiles. Women in the richest quintile exhibit the highest prevalence of caesarean sections at 72.07%. For these wealthiest women, C-sections are nearly three times more common than vaginal deliveries (27.93%). Within the richer and middle quintiles, C-sections constitute the majority of deliveries, accounting for 55.20% and 52.49% of births, respectively. In the poorer quintile, less than half of the women (45.27%) underwent a C-section, with vaginal delivery remaining the slightly more common method at 54.73%. Finally, women in the poorest quintile have the lowest rate of C-section deliveries at 32.25%, with vaginal delivery being the predominant method, representing 67.75% of all births (Figure 7).

Figure 8: Caesarean section and wealth index

4 Conclusion

The analysis of the 2013 DHS data reveals that maternal healthcare utilization is primarily driven by socioeconomic factors rather than demographic variables like age. Household wealth and educational attainment are the strongest predictors of healthcare adherence. Women in the poorest quintile and those with no formal education face the greatest risk of receiving sub-optimal antenatal care, with a significant portion failing to reach the recommended four-visit threshold. Geographic location remains a significant factor in service utilization. Urban residents achieve substantially higher rates of antenatal care coverage at 93%, compared to 79% for their rural counterparts. Furthermore, urban residents achieve nearly universal intranatal care compared to those in rural areas.

A dramatic shift in delivery methods is evident as wealth and education increase. Caesarean sections have become the predominant delivery method for the wealthiest and most educated womenreaching rates above 70%whereas vaginal delivery remains the norm for those with less education and fewer financial resources.

While Turkey has achieved high levels of maternal healthcare coverage, significant disparities persist. Policy efforts should focus on closing the gap for the most vulnerable populationsspecifically women in the poorest households and those with no formal educationto ensure equitable access to essential maternal services.

5 Limitation

While this report provides significant insights into maternal healthcare trends, several limitations should be considered when interpreting the results:

Data Recency: The analysis utilizes data from the 2013 Demographic and Health Survey (DHS); consequently, the findings may not fully reflect the current healthcare landscape or recent policy changes in Turkey.

Focus on Quantity over Quality: The report evaluates the quantity of care (e.g., number of visits) and delivery methods but does not account for the clinical quality of the services, the specific content of care provided, or the medical necessity of Caesarean sections.

Weighting: All analyses in this report were conducted using unweighted data, which may affect the generalizability of the findings to the national population.

Unmeasured Confounders: Other potential confounding variablessuch as health insurance status, geographic proximity to facilities, or specific medical histories were not analyzed in this report.
